1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:03,360
Bitwise operators are used in low level programming,

2

00:00:03,360  -->  00:00:08,660
such as manipulating, which means changing or transforming data at the bit level.

3

00:00:08,660  -->  00:00:11,280
They are important in tasks like setting or checking

4

00:00:11,280  -->  00:00:14,500
the status of specific bits in a byte.

5

00:00:14,500  -->  00:00:18,580
This can be useful in scenarios like managing feature flags such as

6

00:00:18,580  -->  00:00:23,080
make something show or not show in a web application, or device settings.

7

00:00:23,080  -->  00:00:26,840
Think about the settings that you set for your favorite applications.

8

00:00:26,840  -->  00:00:29,280
Wow. That's a lot of technical speak.

9

00:00:29,280  -->  00:00:31,520
Let's think about a real example,

10

00:00:31,520  -->  00:00:35,460
turning on and off specific features in a device.

11

00:00:35,460  -->  00:00:38,260
In this example, we're going to write,

12

00:00:38,260  -->  00:00:40,740
we're going to use the bit wise or operator,

13

00:00:40,740  -->  00:00:45,545
and that will be used to turn on specific features represented by bits.

14

00:00:45,545  -->  00:00:49,130
Each bit in a binary number represents a feature.

15

00:00:49,130  -->  00:00:50,850
By using the or operator,

16

00:00:50,850  -->  00:00:56,030
we can set a desired bits to one enabling those features.

17

00:00:56,030  -->  00:00:57,990
Let's see how this would work.

18

00:00:57,990  -->  00:01:00,290
We'll define a variable called features,

19

00:01:00,290  -->  00:01:05,710
and we'll set that equal to zero b one, two, three, four.

20

00:01:05,710  -->  00:01:09,450
And this is going to be for all features off.

21

00:01:09,450  -->  00:01:15,030
Now, if we want to turn on feature one and three,

22

00:01:15,030  -->  00:01:23,630
what we could do is that we could say features equals features or 0b01 01.

23

00:01:23,630  -->  00:01:28,750
Now, if we were to print bin features.

24

00:01:28,750  -->  00:01:34,730
We're going to get the output of 0b101.

25

00:01:34,730  -->  00:01:37,290
To review, in this demo example here,

26

00:01:37,290  -->  00:01:40,470
we're using a bitwise or operator to set

27

00:01:40,470  -->  00:01:47,890
the variable features to itself combined with 0b01 01,

28

00:01:47,890  -->  00:01:53,800
which turns on specific bits features one and three without changing the others.

29

00:01:53,800  -->  00:01:57,610
Bin function, then prints the binary representation

30

00:01:57,610  -->  00:02:01,550
of features showing which features are on or off.

31

00:02:01,550  -->  00:02:09,030
Python displays this as 0b10 by removing any leading zeros.

32

00:02:09,030  -->  00:02:13,910
In binary, 0b01 01 and

33

00:02:13,910  -->  00:02:19,735
0b101 represent the same number five in decimal.

34

00:02:19,735  -->  00:02:23,380
As the leading zero doesn't change the numbers value.

35

00:02:23,380  -->  00:02:28,880
Python automatically removes unnecessary leading zeros when displaying binary numbers,

36

00:02:28,880  -->  00:02:36,180
so 0b01 01, and is shown as 0b101,

37

00:02:36,180  -->  00:02:38,020
as they are the same number.

38

00:02:38,020  -->  00:02:42,900
Bitwise operators are also useful in optimizing performance.

39

00:02:42,900  -->  00:02:46,505
In systems where memory and processing power are limited.

40

00:02:46,505  -->  00:02:49,560
They allow efficient data manipulation and storage,

41

00:02:49,560  -->  00:02:56,220
making them valuable in embedded systems and other resource constrained environments.
